@xXOriginalSin 8GB VRam never make any sense, since it can bottleneck the card despite the card can do more. For instance, a 16GB VRAM 5060Ti can run some games at 1440p without issue when the 8GB version stutter like crazy. VRAM is cheap, no reason to limit it to 8GB unless it purposely done to sabotage the card.

Watch the Daniel Owen "Don't buy 8GB GPUs in 2025 even for 1080p- RTX 5060 Ti 8GB vs 16GB The Ultimate Comparison!!!" and get f-ing mad as well.

And yes, 9060 8GB is trash too.

@Teja You see i think that is where you are wrong, i have a 4090 equipped pc, have had the 4090 since launch, a 3080ti before that, 3080 before that, 2080ti before that... so ive pretty much always purchased the best i could at the time... anyway the point is i look forward to playing little indie titles just as much as AAA titles... in fact i look forward to indies more because they come frequently and are often great games... i just finished clair obscure yesterday and now im playing monster train 2, on my pc on a large 4k OLED LG display, i cant even tell you what the next AAA game im looking forward to playing is but i can reel off many indies im hyped for including slay 2, silksong etc etc, could go on.

I get thats not the mentality of most gamers, especially many mainstream gamers who are only looking at the next AAA flop to come round. But thats why the price should be right, 8gb easily serves a purpose, if the price is right it gets people into gaming, children or adults on a budget and that means thousands of games that play great, i dont think we should judge entry level hardware based on how it performs in the latest AAA games alone.

Ofcourse the price is garbage ofcourse, thats the issue.

@EarthIsFlat456 im into everything, have handhelds like a steam deck and ally x, have 3 pc's in my home, one with a 2060, one with a 3070ti, both my kids and then mine with the 4090.

The point i was making is there is certainly no shortage of games that are amazing that work on everything which is something mainstream outlets just ignore in favor of asking the question is 8gb good enough for this handfull of balls to the wall graphical powerhouse games, i just dont see the logic. It surprises me even more that digital foundry hop on this narrative because of their deeper understanding of gaming in general but i guess this is what we get when they work more than actually game.

They are good at what they do ofcourse but i do have to ask how much they are actually gamers, hardware unboxed are even worse for it... try to sell how much they are gamers but the only game you ever see steve play is fortnite, tragic really, but they are still good at the work they do.
